TY  - JOUR
T1  - Dispatching and Allocating Servers to Stochastically Failing Networks
AU  - Moses, Michael
Y1  - 1972/02/01
PY  - 1972
DA  - 1972/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.18.6.B289
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.18.6.B289
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - B-289
EP  - B-300
VL  - 18
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The problem considered is that of allocating and dispatching servers to networks whose nodes and/or arcs fail stochastically. A mathematical programming formulation is developed which allocates servers to nodal demands so that expected loss is minimized. From this a zero-one programming problem is formulated to insure whole server allocation and to allow for decreasing service time and cost functions in the number of servers dispatched to a demand. Comparative computer experience with two zero-one codes is reported. Server transfers between subparts of networks, use of the model for prepositioning servers throughout the network and other extensions are discussed in the final section.
AB  - The problem considered is that of allocating and dispatching servers to networks whose nodes and/or arcs fail stochastically. A mathematical programming formulation is developed which allocates servers to nodal demands so that expected loss is minimized. From this a zero-one programming problem is formulated to insure whole server allocation and to allow for decreasing service time and cost functions in the number of servers dispatched to a demand. Comparative computer experience with two zero-one codes is reported. Server transfers between subparts of networks, use of the model for prepositioning servers throughout the network and other extensions are discussed in the final section.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.18.6.B289
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.18.6.B289
Y2  - 2024/03/27
